 shopping and salesmanship. In this process, video stores served as a crucial embodiment of movie culture’s historical move toward increased flexibility, adaptability, and customization.In addition to charting the historical rise and fall of the rental industry, Herbert explores the architectural design of video stores, the social dynamics of retail encounters, the video distribution industry, the proliferation of video recommendation guides, and the often surprising persistence of the video store as an adaptable social space of consumer culture. Drawing on ethnographic fieldwork, cultural geography, and archival research, Videoland provides a wide-ranging exploration of the pivotal role video stores played in the history of motion pictures, and is a must-read for students and scholars of media history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aStores, RetailxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aVideo recordings industryxSocial aspectszUnited States 0aVideo recordings industryxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aVideo rental servicesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aamerican history.  aamerican studies.  aarchitectural design.  aarchival research.  acapitalism.  acommercialization.  aconsumer culture.  aconsumer video.  acultural geography.  acultural studies.  aethnographic fieldwork.  afilm.  aincreased flexibility.  amagnetic tapes.  amaterial commodities.  amedia history.  amotion pictures.  amovie culture.  apublic retail space.  arental industry.  aretrospective.  asocial dynamics.  asocial space.  atangible phase.  aunited states of america.  avideo distribution industry.  avideo recommendation guides.  avideo rental stores.08iTitle is part of eBook package